  "prompt": "What is the nicest library at Columbia to work at?",
  "response": "Columbia University has several libraries that offer great environments for studying and working, each with its own unique atmosphere and amenities. Some of the most popular ones include:\n\n1. **Butler Library**: This is Columbia's largest library and often considered the heart of the university's library system. Its grand architecture and vast collection make it a favorite for many students. The reading rooms, especially the iconic Butler 301, offer a quiet and inspiring environment.\n\n2. **Lehman Social Sciences Library**: Located in the International Affairs Building, Lehman provides a more modern and spacious setting, which is ideal for those working on social science research or projects related to international affairs.\n\n3. **Avery Architectural & Fine Arts Library**: For those interested in architecture, art history, or related subjects, Avery Library offers a specialized collection in a beautiful setting, fostering a serene atmosphere for focused work.\n\n4. **Business and Economics Library in Uris Hall**: Catering primarily to business and economics students, this library provides resources and facilities that are conducive to group work and collaborative projects.\n\n5. **Science & Engineering Library**: Located in the Northwest Corner Building, this library is well-suited for students working in the sciences or engineering, offering state-of-the-art facilities and resources.\n\nEach library offers unique benefits, so the \"nicest\" one can depend on your specific needs and preferences, such as the need for quiet space, access to resources, or subject-specific materials. It can be helpful to explore several libraries to find the one that best suits your work habits and study needs.",
